	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>SPS challenge undermining Africa’s competitiveness on commodity markets</h1>

			
			<h4>
												25 December 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>COMESA Secretary General Sindiso Ngwenya has highlighted Africa’s deteriorating market position in commodity markets. He said that African producers faced difficulties in maintaining their market shares as a result of an ‘inability to overcome structural constraints and modernise its agricultural sector’, particularly with regard to standards compliance. He noted however that regional policy initiatives were under way to try and reverse the situation, including ‘the tripartite agreement between EAC, COMESA and SADC … to collaborate in determining and planning SPS infrastructure that will enhance trade and food security.’ He said ‘empirical evidence shows that countries with less developed SPS infrastructure enjoy a lesser share of intra-regional trade.’ He argued it was up to governments to ‘identify correctly the capacity gaps and prioritise SPS investments’.</p><p>Meanwhile ICTSD has published a paper looking at the treatment of SPS and TBT issues under the various EPAs. This paper provides a detailed assessment of the provisions dealing with SPS and TBTs under the various EPAs which have been initialled and signed by ACP governments, since with the granting of duty-free, quota-free access, SPS and TBT issues have taken on greater significance.</p><p>In the agricultural sector, not only the SPS standards themselves but also the ‘conformity assessment procedures’ are seen as critically important to trade outcomes. The paper notes that ‘procedural or administrative requirements can form, in themselves, significant barriers to trade.’ It also notes that ‘the better the existing regulatory infrastructure, public certification and control systems and private industry leadership, the less additional costs [the exporting country] will face in meeting regulatory and administrative requirements.’</p><p>The report reviews the efforts under the EPAs to get to grips with SPS and TBT issues, through harmonisation and equivalence initiatives and facilitating a greater role of ACP authorities in standard-setting processes. It notes that EPA texts ‘do reflect a realisation of the need for ACP countries to receive assistance to improve the extent of their participation in international standard setting.’ However the EPA texts are criticised for lacking ‘specific details’ which rebalance this reality. Overall the report concludes that ‘EPAs fall short of their promise’, although under certain agreements progress is being made in dealing with such issue of the application of the precautionary principle, ensuring international standards are not un-necessarily exceeded and the procedures for attaining equivalence recognition.</p><p>The report notes that harmonisation and equivalence processes can serve to facilitate access for EU exporters to ACP markets, while marginalising ACP suppliers within both intra and inter-regional trade flows.</p><p>In addition, the inequality in ability to determine standards leads to a situation where on the one hand ‘high income participants, including the EC have become adept at using the international standard setting process to pursue their trade interests’, while ‘the deficient participation and influence of developing countries in elaborating harmonised standards often means that the resulting standards are inappropriate for their situations, technically or financially unachievable for them or absent in areas most useful for them.’</p><p>The greater role of ACP authorities in standard-setting processes which EPA provisions are intended to promote is contrasted with the influence that multinational food and agrochemical companies wield in driving the international harmonisation of standards.</p><p>In terms of improving the contribution of EPAs to meeting the SPS and TBT challenges facing ACP governments, the report calls for:</p>
<ul>

<li>greater use of equivalency agreements in priority sectors (including indications of the detailed procedural steps to be followed linked to concrete and binding timelines for agreement);</li>

<li>increased support for certification of conformity in priority sectors;</li>

<li>clearer, binding commitments on capacity-building support in the field of SPS compliance and verification;</li>

<li>clearer recognition of the pest and disease status of particular ACP regions (and sub-regions of countries), based on international guidelines and practices;</li>

<li>the creation of technical committees of experts on SPS and TBTs to resolve disputes and facilitate trade. </li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
The Post Online, ‘Africa losing market shares in commodity exports’, 4 November 2010 <br />

<a href="http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;news_id=95086&amp;cause_id=1694" target="_self">http://www.tralac.org/cgi-bin/giga.cgi?cmd=cause_dir_news_item&amp;news_...</a>&nbsp;<br />
ICTSD, ‘Sanitary, phytosanitary and technical barriers to trade in the economic partnership agreements between the European Union and the ACP countries’, Issue Paper No. 6, August 2010 <br />
<a href="http://ictsd.org/downloads/2010/09/prevost_web_final.pdf" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/downloads/2010/09/prevost_web_final.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In many ACP countries, achieving SPS compliance and conformity assessment procedures are still a major challenge. This can lead to a progressive marginalisation of ACP suppliers from global trade, as SPS and food safety standards and compliance conformity assessment procedures become stricter. Clearly the priority is to raise the level of SPS compliance and conformity assessment procedures. While the EC has launched a number of initiatives and programmes in these areas, the issue of the commercial sustainability of the recurrent costs incurred in the operation of these institutional arrangements is of critical concern.</p><p>In this context intensifying the dialogue on how to ensure compliance and objective conformity assessments within the financial constraints facing ACP governments and private sector operators needs to be accorded a high priority. This often requires sector-based dialogues, involving well-organised private sector associations, as well as ‘pump-priming’ external assistance.</p><p>Such a targeted approach probably offers the best returns in an era of heightened financial stringency. This would also appear to be a priority in order to avoid the emergence of trade diversion on SPS grounds, arising from efforts to conclude either intra-regional or inter-regional harmonisation or mutual recognition of SPS standards.</p>
		</div>
		
